Check your IP address:
  ip a
Display only your IP via ifconfig:
  ifconfig | grep inet
Change your local IP in the same range using ifconfig:
  ifconfig eth0 $ip $netmask
Via route get ypou default gateway and ping it
  route
  ping $ip
Using dhclient refresh your IP address:
  dhclient -r
Get the IPs of the following hosts via nslookup
  nslookup youtube.com
Install the "wdiff" tool using APT and observe the way it is used:
  sudo apt install wdiff
  wdiff file1 file2
Remove wdiff from the system
  sudo apt remove wdiff
Install "unicorn" from GitHub
  git clone https://github.com/trustedsec/unicorn.git
Retrieve package information from repositories
  apt update
Upgrade your system
  apt upgrade
Open a listener using nc to port 23
  nc -lvp 23
    -l: to open a listener
    -v: to observe the output
    -p: to choose a port
Open a new tab in the CLI and connect via telnet to a friend's IP
  telnet $ip
SSH: Activate ssh service
  service ssh start
Create a new user to establish the connection
  adduser user
Connect to distant machine via ssh
  ssh user@$ip
Write something to a file in a distant machine
  echo "Hacker Day!!!" > hacker.txt
  exit
FTP: Open a file transfer server and share a file with a friend
  service vsftpd start
  adduser user
Connect to FTP server via CLI
  ftp $ip
Connect to FTP using browser
  ftp://$ip
SMB: Open a shared folder in the network using SMB
  nano /etc/samba/smbd_config
    [Folders_Name]
      path=<The/Directory>
      guest ok = yes
      browseable = yes
      read only = no
Open SMB service
  service smbd start
Connect to a shared folder using Windows
  Winkey - r
  \\$ip

